Suppose the Linked List is  
1 -> 2 -> 2 -> 3 -> 3

We first take a temporary pointer and point to the Head of the List, then we traverse the List. 
If at any moment we find the value of the next of the temporary pointer with itself is same, we simply delete the next of the temporary pointer and go on traversing our list.

# Code:-
```
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* deleteDuplicates(ListNode* head) {
        if(head==NULL) return head;
        ListNode *temp = head;
        while(temp->next) {
            if(temp->val == temp->next->val) {
                ListNode *link = temp->next;
                temp->next = temp->next->next; 
                delete link;
            }
            else {
                temp = temp->next;
            }
        }
        return head;
    }
};
```

Read below for more clarification:-
for list:- **1 -> 2 -> 2 -> 3 -> 3**
# Step 1:-
temp = 1
temp->next = 2,
here both are different hence we go in the else part.
The List Now becomes:-
**1->2->2->3->3**

# Step 2:-
temp = 2
temp->next = 2
here as both are same, we store the temp->next in **link** node(so that we can free memory later) and disrupt the connection of temp(2) with temp->next(2) and make temp with temp->next->next(3).
After this step, we need to free the memory of the deleted Node.
The List Now becomes:-
**1->2->3->3**

# Step 3:-
temp = 2
temp->next = 3,
here both are different hence we go in the else part.
The List Now becomes:-
**1->2->3->3**

# Step 4:-
temp = 3
temp->next = 3
Here, again as both are same, we just follow the same procedure in **Step2**.
The List Now becomes:-
**1->2->3**

# Step 5:-
temp=3
temp->next = NULL
Now our while condition becomes false, hence we move out of the loop.


# 💀DANGER💀:-
We must provide a check condition at the beginning of our code, to handle the case of **[]**, else we are bound the get a Run Time Error.

At the end, we return the Head with the modified Linked List.

