## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- We are going to use the 2pointers approach.
- Take 2 variables i & j.
- At any point, if i≠0, then it will swap with j & j will be only moved after the swap().
- If any point i & j both indicates 0 then only i will move and j will keep track of 0.
- **Time complexity:** O(n).

### Solution 02

- Here I’ll use a queue to keep track of the indexes of 0.
- If the current index has 0, we’ll push the index***(i)*** to queue.
- If the current element is not 0 & the queue have element, then we’ll take the front element of the queue (mainly the index of the first 0).
- Put the current non 0 element to that index & place 0 to the current index. Push the current index to queue because it has 0 now! *[simply we swap the current element with the first index available in the queue & push current index as that have 0 now]*.
- Remove the first element using pop(), because queue remove element from front.
- **Time complexity:** O(n).

---

## Code:

```cpp
//Solution 01:
class Solution {
public:
    void moveZeroes(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n= nums.size();
        int i=0, j=0;

        while(i<n){
            if(nums[i]!=0){
                swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
                i++; j++;
            }
            else 
                i++;
        }
    }
};

//Solution 02:
class Solution {
public:
    void moveZeroes(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n= nums.size();
        queue<int> add;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            if(nums[i]==0)
                add.push(i);
            else{
                if(!add.empty()){
                    int x=add.front();
                    nums[x]=nums[i];
                    nums[i]=0;
                    add.push(i);
                    add.pop();
                }
            }
        }
    }
};
```

