We can use binary search in this problem but there are two parameters are varying.
**1) No of digits which will requires for represnting N in base 'b'** *(we will fix this parameter)*
**2) base 'b' itself**  *(we will do binary search on this parameter)*

so we have to fix one parameter and do binary search on another parameter.

In our case the range of input number is known which is  10^ 18 . . .
hence we can fix the number of digits and iterate over all possible number of digit and apply binary search on base.

now 
**max number of digit = log2(10^18) [Approximately 60]
min number of digit = 2 [why not 1 ? because n^0 will always be 1 . .]**

one more concept ->
base is inversely proportional to number of digits with which we can represent n. . 
since we want to minimize base we will start from highest number of digits which is 60 in our case and iterate till 3 . . 

since minimum number of digit can be 2. . .in that case our answer will be n-1
[ 
		why ?
		if number of digi will be 2 then 
		n = base^1 +base^0   =>  n = base +1    =>  base = n-1
]

so for i digits
**n = 1 + b^1 + b^2 + b^3+ . . . + b^i**

it looks like gemoatric progration
 **n = (b^i - 1) / (b-1)**

**n(b-1) =  (b^i - 1)**

we will apply binary search on base
start = 2;
end = n;

lhs = n(b-1)
rhs =(b^i - 1)

if
lhs=rhs =>mid is our anwer
if lhs > rhs then start = mid+1
else end =mid -1


    public static String solve(String A) {

        BigInteger NUM = new BigInteger(A);

        int maxDigits = (int)Math.ceil(Math.log(1e18)/Math.log(2));
        int minDigits = 2;
        // why we starting from a maxvalue?
        // because base is inversly proprtional to no of digits. . .so to get minimum base we have to start with maximum no of digits which 60 in our case
        for(int i = maxDigits ; i>minDigits ;i--){
