# Approach
funEval function evaluates the following function
f(x,ones) = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + ... + x^(ones-1);

Now, what does f(x,ones) basically means? 
f(x,ones) gives the decimal value of 111...1(repeated ones times) which is in base x;

If you could not understand the above, you needs some basics of number system and algebra. 

Now, since we are asked to find the smallest base, we start with largest number of ones which I took 72. As obviously, more the number of ones, lower would be the base. 

That's it. Now you just binary search to find the value of x. If x exists, return it else continue with reducing one. 




Extra Info: The last line of the code which is return num would never be reached or in other words, solution will always exists. 
And it is n-1, and base n-1 number would be 11. 




# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    long long funEval(int ones, long long x){
        long long res = 1;
        long long last = 1;
        long long mx = numeric_limits<long long>::max();
        for(int i=1;i<ones;i++){
            if (last > mx/x) return mx;
            last *=x;
            if (res > mx - last) return mx;
            res += last;
        }
        return res;
    }

    string smallestGoodBase(string num) {
        long long number = stoll(num);
        for(int ones = 72; ones >=2; ones--){
            long long left = 2;
            long long right = number-1;
            while(left <= right){
                long long mid = left/2 + right/2;
                if ( (left&1) && (right&1) ) mid++;
                long long value = funEval(ones, mid);
                if (value == number) return to_string(mid);
                if (value > number){
                    right = mid-1;
                }
                else left = mid+1;
            }
        }
        return num;
    }
};
```

