# Intuition
In base k we should have n = 1 + k + k^2 + ... k^{m}, i.e. we need to find smallest k such that there exists an m with (k^{m+1}-1)/(k-1). Obesrve that 2 <= m <= Log(n). So for each m in this range we do a binary search to find k. As a result we return the smallest k found. 

Took quitesome efforts to align all the edge cases with overflow, so at some point I decided to use BigInteger...


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution 
{
    public string SmallestGoodBase(string n) 
    {
        var target = BigInteger.Parse(n);
        var result = target - 1;

        for(int m = 2; m <= 2 * BigInteger.Log(target); ++m)
        {
            BigInteger left = 2;
            BigInteger right = target + 10;

            while(left <= right)
            {
                var temp = left + (right - left)/2;
                var sum = (BigInteger.Pow(temp, m) - 1);

                if( sum == target * (temp - 1))
                {   
                    result = BigInteger.Min(result, temp);
                    break;
                }

                if( sum < target * (temp - 1))
                {
                    left = temp + 1;
                }
                else
                {
                    right = temp - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return result.ToString();
    }
}
```

