solutions.content:
So, the number in base b must be 1 + b + b^2 + ...
Solution with two digits is b = n - 1.
To find longer, better solutions, loop number of digits from 3 to 63 (break if binary representation > n)
For a given number of digits, the upper bound of the base b is pow(n-1, 1.0/(digits-1)) (+ 1 for safety against rounding errors). Then we can simply reduce the base until the sum is < n. There will be max 3 candidate bases for a given number of digits.
```
public String smallestGoodBase(String s) {
        int limit = 0;
        long n = Long.parseLong(s);
        long best = n - 1;
out:    for (int digits = 3; digits < 64; digits++) {
            if (digits > limit) System.out.println("" + digits + " digits");
            double d = Math.pow(n - 1, 1.0/(digits - 1));
            if (digits > limit) System.out.println(d);
in:         for (long base = (long) d + 1; base >= 2; base--) {
                long sum = Long.MAX_VALUE;
                long[] powers = new long[digits];
                powers[0] = 1;
                sum = 1;
                for (int i = 1; i < digits; i++) {
                    powers[i] = powers[i - 1] * base;
                    if (powers[i] < 0) {
                        continue in;
                    }
                    sum += powers[i];
                }
                if (digits > limit) System.out.println(Arrays.toString(powers) + " " + sum + ((sum == n)? " new best":""));
                if (sum > n && base == 2) {
                    break out;
                }
                if (sum == n) {
                    best = base;
                    break;
                }
                if (sum < n) {
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return Long.toString(best);
    }
