solutions.content:
This is a problem that IMHO should rated as hard, since it requires at least 2 different patterns (branching from a graph to get the different characters and DP) with a twist.

In order to tackle it, we will declare at class level `dp` as a pointer to a pointer of an `int` and then initialise it in the main function for it to be referring to a 2 dimensional array with `w1.size()` rows of `w2.size()` elements each, all initialised to be `INT_MAX` to mark them as untouched.

Focusing on the graph part, we will solve it with `dfs`, which initially will be passed only the 2 input strings and will also take as optional parameters 2 pointers `i` and `j` (for characters in `w1` and `w2`, respectively), both defaulted to `0` (ie: to point to the first character of each string). In this function we will check all the possibilities we can get to :
* first we are going to declare 2 support variables `l1` and `l2` with the leftover characters to parse in each string;
* we do so since we want to check if we are done parsing either string (ie: either `i` or `j` match the length of their respective string) and if so, we know that we have to just remove all the leftover characters in the other string (and thus if we ended up parsing both string at the same time, we would just `return` `0` here);
* then we activate our memoisation super power and check if we already encountered this scenario - the most efficient solution for these very same `i` and `j` and if so (said value is `!= INT_MAX`), we can just `return` it;
* then we have the case where `i` and `j` point to the same character: in this case no replacement needs to be done (ie: no character needs to be skipped) and we can `return` a recursive call to `dfs` after increasing both of them;
* the last, general case is when `i` and `j` point to different characters, in which case we will store in `dp[i][j]` `1` (since we know at least one character has to be removed here), plus the minimum value between a recursive call increasing `i` (ie: skipping/ignoring the current character) and a recursive call increasing `j`.

At the end of our calls, we will be returning the smaller possible value to make the string equal, without actually having to generate any.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
    int **dp;
public:
    int dfs(string &w1, string &w2, int i = 0, int j = 0) {
        // support variables
        int l1 = w1.size() - i, l2 = w2.size() - j;
        // end case: finished parsing at least one string
        if (!l1 || !l2) {
            // no character to be removed if both are finished, otherwise we remove the remaining ones
            return max(l1, l2);
        }
        // looking for already stored value
        if (dp[i][j] != INT_MAX) return dp[i][j];
        // matching characters case: no removal on either string
        if (w1[i] == w2[j]) return dfs(w1, w2, ++i, ++j);
        // general case: computing and memoising it
        return dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dfs(w1, w2, i + 1, j), dfs(w1, w2, i, j + 1));
    }
    int minDistance(string w1, string w2) {
        // resizing dp
        dp = new int*[w1.size()];
        for (int i = 0, lmt = w1.size(); i < lmt; i++) {
            dp[i] = new int[w2.size()];
            fill(dp[i], dp[i] + w2.size(), INT_MAX);
        }
        return dfs(w1, w2);
    }
};
```

