# Dp
## Complexity
- TC (Time Complexity): The time complexity of the updated code is O(m * n), where m and n are the lengths of the input strings. The code uses a bottom-up dynamic programming approach to calculate the length of the Longest Common Subsequence (LCS) between the two strings. It iterates over each character in both strings once, filling the dp matrix with the lengths of the LCS for various substrings. Since each cell in the matrix is filled based on previous computations, the overall time complexity is O(m * n).e.
- SC (Space Complexity): The space complexity of the updated code is O(m * n) because it uses a 2D matrix (DP) of size (m+1) x (n+1) to store the lengths of the LCS for different substrings. Each cell in the matrix represents a subproblem and stores the length of the LCS up to that point. Therefore, the space required is proportional to the lengths of the input strings. The rest of the variables and data structures used in the code have constant space requirements.
