# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Here, we have to tell the number of operations we need to perform in order to be able to convert a string into toally new given string. We know this is possible. To accomplish this, the max number of operations will be performing would be deleting all the characters of string1 and then later adding all the characters of string2 to string1. But to find out the minimum number of operations, we would have to retain longest common subsequence in string1 and string2. Then, we would be performing our insertions accoding to the need.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Write the function for finding out the longest common subsequence. Then the number of deletions in string1 would be string1.size() - lcs(string1, string2). And number of insertions would be string2.size()-lcs(string1, string2). And giving out the number of insertions plus deletions in  this case would give the number of minimum oprations required for doing this change. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N*M)---There are two nested loops.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N*M)---We are using an external array of size (N*M). Stack Space is eliminated.

