# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem is we need to the find the minimum number of deletions to make strings equal while preserving the subsequence.

Since we have to to maintain the subsequence we need to find the longest common subsequence betweent the strings.




# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First we will find the longest common subsequene out of the two strings. We will use dynamic approach to find the longest subsequnce using it.

Next step is to find the number of deletions need to perform to make the strings same. 

For this first find the deletions required from each string and add them up.

Ex - 
int ans = w1 - dp[0][0] + w2 - dp[0][0];

w1 - dp[0][0] --> number of deletion from 1st string
 w2 - dp[0][0] --> number of deletion from 2nd string
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
TC - m*n 
where m and n is length of the strings

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

SC - m*n
For maintaining the dp array

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minDistance(String word1, String word2) {
        int w1 = word1.length();
        int w2 = word2.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[w1+1][w2+1];

        for(int i = w1-1; i>=0; i--) {
            for(int j = w2-1; j>=0; j--) {
                if(word1.charAt(i) == word2.charAt(j))
                dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i+1][j+1];
                else
                dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j+1]);
            }
        }
        int ans = w1 - dp[0][0] + w2 - dp[0][0];
        return ans;
    }
}
```

